<p><i><b>Kyōiku kanji</b></i> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji" lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">教育漢字</span><span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Installing_Japanese_character_sets" title="Help:Installing Japanese character sets"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>, literally "education kanji")</span>, also known as <i><b>Gakunenbetsu kanji haitōhyō</b></i> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji" lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">学年別漢字配当表</span><span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Installing_Japanese_character_sets" title="Help:Installing Japanese character sets"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>, literally "list of kanji by <a href="/wiki/School_year" title="School year" class="mw-redirect">school year</a>")</span> is a list of 1,006 <a href="/wiki/Kanji" title="Kanji">kanji</a> and associated readings developed and maintained by the <a href="/wiki/Ministry_of_Education,_Culture,_Sports,_Science_and_Technology_(Japan)" title="Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology (Japan)" class="mw-redirect">Japanese Ministry of Education</a> that prescribes which kanji, and which readings of kanji, Japanese schoolchildren should learn for each year of primary school. Although the list is designed for Japanese children, it can also be used as a sequence of learning characters by non-native speakers as a means of focusing on the most commonly used kanji.</p>
<p>Kyōiku kanji is a subset of <a href="/wiki/J%C5%8Dy%C5%8D_kanji" title="Jōyō kanji">Jōyō kanji</a>.</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Versions_of_ky.C5.8Diku_list">Versions of kyōiku list</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Ky%C5%8Diku_kanji&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Versions of kyōiku list">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Ky%C5%8Diku_kanji&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Versions of kyōiku list" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:3002_Kanji.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/3002_Kanji.svg/300px-3002_Kanji.svg.png" width="300" height="282" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/3002_Kanji.svg/450px-3002_Kanji.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/3002_Kanji.svg/600px-3002_Kanji.svg.png 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:3002_Kanji.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf12/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A list of all <a href="/wiki/J%C5%8Dy%C5%8D_kanji" title="Jōyō kanji">jōyō kanji</a> according to <a href="/wiki/Kodansha_Kanji_Learner%27s_Dictionary" title="Kodansha Kanji Learner's Dictionary">Halpern's KKLD indexing system</a>, with kyōiku kanji coloured according to grade level.</div>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>1946 created with 881 characters</li>
<li>1977 expanded to 996 characters</li>
<li>1982 expanded to 1,006 characters</li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="The_list_by_grade">The list by grade</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Ky%C5%8Diku_kanji&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: The list by grade">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Ky%C5%8Diku_kanji&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: The list by grade" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Note 1: Many kanji have complex meanings and nuances, or express concepts not directly translatable into English. In those cases, the English meanings mentioned here constitute approximations.</p>
<p>Note 2: In the <a href="/wiki/Kanji#Kun.27yomi_.28Japanese_reading.29" title="Kanji">Kun</a> readings, readings after - (hyphen) are <a href="/wiki/Okurigana" title="Okurigana">Okurigana</a>.</p>
